docs.abstract: Officials ordered Daimler to recall more than 700,000 diesel vehicles, and said a member of VW’s management board was under scrutiny in an inquiry into emissions-cheating.
docs.snippet: Officials ordered Daimler to recall more than 700,000 diesel vehicles, and said a member of VW’s management board was under scrutiny in an inquiry into emissions-cheating.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Germany’s car industry, already under scrutiny for concealing excess diesel pollution, suffered fresh damage to its reputation on Monday after prosecutors said a top Volkswagen manager was a suspect in a criminal inquiry, and authorities in Berlin ordered Daimler to recall hundreds of thousands of vehicles equipped with illegal emissions-cheating software.

headline.main: Diesel Scandal Deepens as German Authorities Target Audi Chief and Daimler
headline.print_headline: Germany’s Diesel Morass Just Got Deeper and Wider

docs.abstract: The European counterattack, a response to U.S. measures on steel and aluminum, adds another front to a trade war that has engulfed allies and adversaries around the world.
docs.snippet: The European counterattack, a response to U.S. measures on steel and aluminum, adds another front to a trade war that has engulfed allies and adversaries around the world.
docs.lead_paragraph: GOTEBORG, Sweden — The European Union fought back on Friday against the Trump administration’s tariffs, slapping penalties on an array of American products that target the president’s political base, like bourbon, motorcycles and orange juice.

headline.print_headline: Europe Wages Counterattack In Trade War

docs.abstract: The carmaker will pay one of the largest penalties ever imposed on a company in postwar Germany to settle accusations that it failed to properly supervise employees who violated clean air rules.
docs.snippet: The carmaker will pay one of the largest penalties ever imposed on a company in postwar Germany to settle accusations that it failed to properly supervise employees who violated clean air rules.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Even after Volkswagen was hit with billions of dollars in penalties in the United States over an emissions-cheating scheme that continues to unfold, the company remained mostly unpunished in Europe.

headline.main: Volkswagen Agrees to $1.2 Billion German Fine in Emissions-Cheating Scheme
headline.print_headline: Germany, Following Lead of U.S., Fines VW Over Emissions, Collecting $1.2 Billion
